    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, using smart pointers such as `std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr` largely abstracts away memory management concerns, as they automatically manage the lifetime of the object they point to. When a smart pointer goes out of scope, its destructor is called and any dynamically allocated memory it manages is automatically released.\n\nTake `std::make_unique<double>(value)` as an example, it creates a `std::unique_ptr<double>` that takes ownership of the allocated `double`. When the `unique_ptr` goes out of scope, the memory is freed automatically. Therefore, you don't need to manually call `delete`.\n\nHere is an example using `std::make_unique`:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <memory>\n\nvoid processTransactions(int numTransactions) {\n    for (int i = 0; i < numTransactions; ++i) {\n        auto txAmount = std::make_unique<double>(100.0 + i); \n        // Now, there's no need to delete since unique_ptr will release the memory when it goes out of scope.\n        std::cout << \"Processing transaction \" << i << \": \" << *txAmount << std::endl;\n        double result = (*txAmount)",
